\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The\~}{\f1\fs24\b1\i1 Tanya}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~(}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hebrew_language"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Hebrew}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 :\~\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u1514\'3F\u1504\'3F\u1497\'3F\u1488\'3F) is an early work of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hasidic_philosophy"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Hasidic philosophy}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , by Rabbi\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shneur_Zalman_of_Liadi"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Shneur Zalman of Liadi}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , the founder of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chabad"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Chabad}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~Hasidism, first published in 1796. Its formal title is\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Likkutei Amarim}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~(\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u1500\'3F\u1497\'3F\u1511\'3F\u1493\'3F\u1496\'3F\u1497\'3F \u1488\'3F\u1502\'3F\u1512\'3F\u1497\'3F\u1501\'3F\u8206\'3F,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hebrew_language"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Hebrew}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , "collection of statements"), but is more commonly known by its first Hebrew word\~}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 tanya}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , which means "it has been taught", where he refers to a\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baraita"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 baraita}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~section in\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niddah_(Talmud)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "Niddah"}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , at the end of chapter 3, 30b. Tanya is composed of five sections that define Hasidic mystical psychology and theology as a handbook for daily spiritual life in Jewish observance. }
